   <abstract>Scholars have been utilizing the inquisition period and the blood purity statutes put into effect in fifteenth-century Spain in order to define and outline antisemitism as we know it today, as well as disregard the notion that race has been an ever-evolving concept that did not just begin with the emergence of genetics in the 18th century. Conceptually, it seemed as though the formulation of the idea of Jewish people as a race aligned heavily with Nazi propaganda in the 1930s. Thus, medieval Spanish works, such as El Retablo de las Maravillas by Miguel de Cervantes, began to be examined through two distinct lenses: the basis for modern day antisemitism, and the foundations of racism. However, much of what is known about the society of medieval Spain today demonstrates that the concept of race was more of a social construct than a biological one. Spanish society was heavily influenced by politics, using religion as a foundation for understanding the world, and the constant anxiety that one's social status could change overnight. Cervantes' work and the societal structures of 15th century Spain must be returned to and left in their own time period. Looking at the parallels drawn between Nazi Germany's treatment of Jews and Spain's inquisition period through El Retablo de las Maravillas, in addition to analyzing the distinct meanings of the terms "raza" and "race", provides us with in depth understanding and the integral ability to distinguish the two time periods.</abstract>
